@node "Bugs" "Bugs    "
As far as I am aware, there are no bugs in CrapTrack.
@endnode

@node "Why?" "Why?    "
CrapTrack is the ultimate back-to-basics tracker.  Writing a good module with
CrapTrack requires musical ability and a gift for melody, not a technical gift
for knowing exactly when to use a C64-style chord warble or an AREXX script.
It is also a test of patience.

Alternatively, it is just crap, but in a funky, skillo sort of way.
@endnode

@node "Instructions" "Instructions"
@{b}@{u}Instructions@{ub}@{uu}

Creating a CrapTrack module is fairly easy.  I recommend looking at the
included examples in the "Modules" directory to see how a module should be
written.


 @{"Editing       " link "Editing" 0}

 @{"File Structure" link "Structure" 0}
 @{"Commands      " link "Commands" 0}

 @{"Notes         " link "Notes" 0}
@endnode

@node "Med2Crp" "Med2Crp"
A slightly easier method of creating CrapTrack modules is to write them using
OctaMED, then convert them to CrapTrack format using the Med2Crp utility.  In
order to achieve this, the modules must only use 4 channels of sound.  Also
note that these instructions pertain specifically to OctaMED Sound Studio,
though I am fairly sure that at least OctaMED Pro 6, and possibly Pro 5, work
in the same way.

Step-by-step instructions:

  1. Load the module for conversion into OctaMED.
  2. Select "Print" from the "Project" menu.
  3. Click on the "All Blocks" button.
  4. Select an output file.
  5. "Print" the document to the file.
  6. Save all instruments from the module as IFF-8SVX samples into a suitable
directory.
  7. Load the Med2Crp utility.
  8. Click the "Input" button.
  9. Select the file you saved using OctaMED.
 10. Click the "Output" button.
 11. Select an ouput file to save.

The module is now converted into CrapTrack format.  To be able to play the
module, all you need to do next is insert the necessary "inst" or "loop"
commands into its header using a text editor.  After you have done this, you
can load the module into the CrapTrack program and play it back.

Note that all data except notes, octaves and instrument numbers, is
discarded.

One limitation of the Med2Crp utility is that it does not sequence the blocks
into the order that OctaMED uses.  Imagine a song which uses blocks in the
following order:

 00
 01
 00
 01
 02

The Med2Crp utility will just re-sequence this as:

 00
 01
 02

In order to circumvent this limitation, you must either manually change the
sequence of the blocks in the resulting CrapTrack module (all blocks have an
empty line between them), or extrapolate the playing sequence within OctaMED
before beginning the conversion.
@endnode

@node "Structure" "File Structure"
A CrapTrack module is divided up into two parts.  These are the "header" and
the "note information".

 @{"The Header          " link "Header" 0}
 @{"The Note Information" link "NoteInfo" 0}
@endnode

@node "Header" "The Header"
A typical header looks like this:

@{fg shine}
 CRPTRK10

 author Ant
 title Dragon's Lair
 comment Med2Trk

 inst 00 samples/sample1
 inst 01 samples/sample2@{fg text}


Of these, only two commands are actually necessary.  These are the first
command, "@{"CRPTRK10" link "CRPTRK10" 0}", and the "@{"inst" link "inst" 0}" command.  The others, "@{"author" link "authorcmd" 0}", "@{"title" link "title" 0}"
and "@{"comment" link "comment" 0}", just allow the module to report some information about its
creator.
@endnode

@node "CRPTRK10" "CRPTRK10"
@{fg shine}CRPTRK10@{fg text}

Syntax: CRPTRK10

This command identifies the file as a CrapTrack module.  It @{b}must@{ub} be placed at
the very start of a module.
@endnode

@node "inst" "inst"
@{fg shine}inst@{fg text}

Syntax: inst <sample number> <path>

This command should be placed in the header of a module.  It loads an IFF-8SVX
sample into the module when it is played back.  Sample number @{b}must@{ub} be a
two-digit figure.  If the number only has one digit (ie. it is less than 10)
then use the format 00, 01, 02, and so on.

Path is the complete name and path of the sample, relative to the location of
the module.

Example:

inst 01 /samples/sample1
@endnode

@node "authorcmd" "author"
@{fg shine}author@{fg text}

Syntax: author <author name>

This is an optional command that displays the author's name in the CrapTrack
window. The name can be up to 18 characters long.

Example:

author Ant
@endnode

@node "title" "title"
@{fg shine}title@{fg text}

Syntax: title <module name>

This is an optional command that displays the module's name in the CrapTrack
window. The name can be up to 18 characters long.

Example:

title Song40
@endnode

@node "comment" "comment"
@{fg shine}comment@{fg text}

Syntax: comment <text>

"Comment" is an optional command that displays a comment in the CrapTrack
window.  The comment can be up to 18 characters long.

Example:

comment This is crap!
@endnode

@node "NoteInfo" "The Note Information"
The second part of the file is begun with the "module" command.  After this
comes the note information itself.  Thus:

@{fg shine} module
 D-2-00:B-1-01:B-2-02:G#2-02@{fg text}

The "module" command separates the header from the footer.  The second line
above is the actual module data itself.  This is structure thus:

@{fg shine} Note-Octave-Sample@{fg text}

So, to play back sample number 00, using the second available octave at pitch
"A", one uses the command:

@{fg shine} A-2-00@{fg text}

For "A sharp", this is modified to:

@{fg shine} A#2-00@{fg text}

As the Amiga has four channels of audio, each line must give instructions for
every channel.  Channel information is separated using a colon, ":".  So:

@{fg shine} A#2-00:C-2-01:C-3-02:C-1-03@{fg text}

If you do not want to play another sound, and wish the current sample to
continue playing, simply use the command "------" instead of specifying a
note:

@{fg shine} A#2-00:C-2-01:------:C-1-03@{fg text}

If you want the current sound to stop playing, use the command "XXXXXX":

@{fg shine} A#2-00:C-2-01:XXXXXX:C-1-03@{fg text}

Example modules are included in the "Modules" directory.
@endnode

@node "Commands" "Commands"
This is a list of all of the available commands.


@{b}Header commands:@{ub}

 @{"CRPTRK10" link "CRPTRK10" 0}
 @{"author  " link "authorcmd" 0}
 @{"title   " link "title" 0}
 @{"comment " link "comment" 0}
 @{"tempo   " link "tempo" 0}
 @{"inst    " link "inst" 0}
 @{"loop    " link "loop" 0}

@{b}
Note information commands:@{ub}

 @{"module  " link "module" 0}
 @{"XXXXXX  " link "XXXXXX" 0}
 @{"------  " link "------" 0}
@endnode

@node "loop" "loop"
@{fg shine}loop@{fg text}

Syntax: loop <sample number> <path>

This command functions identically to the "@{"inst" link "inst" 0}" command, except samples
loaded using it will be looped when played back.  The loop information is read
from the IFF-8SVX sample itself.

Example:

loop 01 samples/sample1
@endnode

@node "tempo" "tempo"
@{fg shine}tempo@{fg text}

Syntax: tempo <value>

This sets the tempo of the module, in vertical blanks.  A tempo of 1 will play
a new note every vertical blank, whereas a value of 10 will play a new note
every 10 vertical blanks.  In essence, the higher the number, the slower the
song.

The default value is 5.

Example:

tempo 4
@endnode

@node "module" "module"
@{fg shine}module@{fg text}

Syntax: module

This separates the header from the note information.  It @{b}must@{ub} come immediately
before the note information, or the module will not play.

Example:

 module
 D-2-01:D-2-02:------:XXXXXX
 ------:------:------:------
@endnode

@node "XXXXXX" "XXXXXX"
@{fg shine}XXXXXX@{fg text}

Syntax: XXXXXX

This is used in place of a note, and stops the current sample playing.

Example:

D-2-01:XXXXXX:D-2-01:D-2-01
@endnode

@node "------" "------"
@{fg shine}------@{fg text}

Syntax: ------

This is effectively a "gap".  CrapTrack will do nothing upon meeting this
command. Samples currently playing will continue to play.

Example:

D-2-01:------:D-2-01:D-2-01
@endnode

@node "Notes" "Notes"
 - Samples must be in IFF-8SVX format, or CrapTrack will probably crash.
 - CrapTrack will play notes between the range C-1 and B-3.
 - The number of samples is limited to 30.
 - Inserting line returns inside the note information section of the module,
in order to split the module into "blocks", is permissible.
@endnode

@node "Editing" "Editing"
To edit a CrapTrack module, just load up your favourite text editor and begin.
Note that CrapTrack expects Amiga-style line returns, not PC-style line and
carriage returns.
@endnode

@node "Examples" "Examples    "
There are three example modules included in the "Modules" drawer.  These are:

@{b}@{u}Example.crp@{ub}@{uu}

This was labouriously typed by hand into "Ed".@{b}@{u}

DragonsLair.crp@{ub}@{uu}

This is the same module, but converted from the OctaMED original.

@{b}@{u}Song43.crp@{ub}@{uu}

This was also converted from an OctaMED module.

@{b}@{u}Song75.crp@{ub}@{uu}

As was this.
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
CrapTrack requires:

 - An Amiga
 - Workbench 2+
 - A text editor.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
To install CrapTrack, simply copy the CrapTrack directory to somewhere on your
hard drive, then copy the contents of the Fonts/ directory to FONTS:
@endnode

@node "Copyright" "Copyright"
CrapTrack is Copyright © DAS Software 2002.  It is freeware, and as such is
freely distributable as long as all files in the archive remain intact.

CrapTrack can be included on magazine coverdisks/cover CDs, but I would like
to be notified.  I would prefer to receive a free copy of the magazine, or
just the CD, but this is simply a curtesy and is not strictly necessary.  Disk
mags are also free to include CrapTrack if they wish, as are websites, etc.

Modules written using CrapTrack are of course freely distributable.  The
CrapTrack executable can be included with such modules without the rest of the
archive.  This is the only instance when the archive can be split and
distributed separately.

If you are crazy enough to write a module using CrapTrack, please email me and
let me know about it!
@endnode

@node "Disclaimer" "Disclaimer"
CrapTrack has been tested thoroughly using an A1200T 060/50MHz, an A100
030/40MHz and WinUAE running Amiga apps at what looks like 20x the speed of
the above A1200T. However, you use CrapTrack at your own risk.  I cannot be
held responsible for:

